WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.680
Good morning from New Zealand, where I'm currently staying for a couple of weeks.

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:17.440
But wherever you are in the world, welcome.

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:24.000
So as Lachan said, I wanted to talk a little bit about multi-lingual data science.

00:00:24.559 --> 00:00:30.400
Hopefully I don't need to belabor too much why this is important,

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:37.200
because I think it's pretty obvious that every team has to deal with multiple languages,

00:00:37.759 --> 00:00:44.160
because regardless of whether you use R or Python or Julia, you have to use SQL as well.

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:49.200
There's no getting away from it. We kind of strongly believe that there's no way to...

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:53.840
It would be awesome if we could all just standardize on one single language,

00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:59.279
but that's never going to happen. So rather than fretting about it, rather than worrying about it,

00:00:59.279 --> 00:01:01.759
rather than letting it stress us out, let's embrace it.

00:01:02.959 --> 00:01:08.400
Let's embrace the different strengths and weaknesses of various languages and really

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:13.839
think about how can we help teams of folks using different tools work together as effectively as

00:01:13.839 --> 00:01:20.160
possible. So today I kind of wanted to talk about three things. The first, as Logan said,

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:28.480
is to share a little bit of my love for R. R is like a weird language. It's definitely got some

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:35.839
quirks, things that don't make sense, but it also has a few things that seem surprising when you

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:41.199
first hit them, if you've used a language like Python particularly. You're going to see these

00:01:41.199 --> 00:01:47.279
things and think, wow, that is really, really weird. And I want to talk a lot about some of

00:01:47.279 --> 00:01:52.559
that weirdness and why it's not wrong, it's just different. And in fact, it leads to some pretty

00:01:52.559 --> 00:01:58.480
cool and surprising features. Then I want to talk a little bit about the sort of journey from R

00:01:58.480 --> 00:02:03.519
Studio to Posit, like why do we change our names, what's kind of our mission as a company, and then

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:08.800
dive into some of the tools that we are really working on currently that are, again, not about

00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:13.600
that idea of how do we help multilingual teams work together as effectively as possible.

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:22.399
So I'm going to start with three surprising features of R. And these things are surprising

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:29.279
because when you hit them at first, they might not seem like features. They might seem like

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:35.759
bugs. And they're certainly going to feel very weird coming from just about any other programming

00:02:35.759 --> 00:02:41.279
language. So I want to kind of highlight some of those, talk about why they're actually cool

00:02:41.279 --> 00:02:47.600
and interesting, and show you a little bit of R code along the way. So for context,

00:02:48.399 --> 00:02:54.800
the job of me and my team primarily is to develop the tidyverse, which is a collection of R packages

00:02:54.800 --> 00:03:03.199
that make data science fast, fluent, and fun. But we also develop tools that software engineers use,

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:08.320
tools for package development in R, things like Roxygen 2 for inline documentation,

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:15.839
test that for unit testing, package down for beautiful packages, and use this for automating

00:03:15.839 --> 00:03:23.440
every part of the package development process that you possibly can. So all up, we spend a lot

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:30.000
of our time kind of thinking about user interfaces, thinking about how we can make data analysis

00:03:30.559 --> 00:03:38.000
as pleasant, as enjoyable, as fluent as possible for data scientists. And similarly, how can we

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.279
do the same thing for kind of when you switch hats from your data scientist hat to your software

00:03:43.279 --> 00:03:51.600
engineering hat, how can we help you make robust, reliable packages as easily and painlessly as

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:57.919
possible? So I'm going to show you a little R code shortly, and I'm going to motivate that code.

00:03:57.919 --> 00:04:03.520
What I'm going to do is make a scatterplot. So this scatterplot is on the x-axis. You can see

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:08.559
we've got distance, and on the y-axis, we've got speed, and then we've got a bunch of dots.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:16.320
And each of these dots represents a route of a flight in the continental US. So in origin and

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:20.959
destination, we've got some data about those flights, which I'll show you shortly. What we've

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:25.920
done is aggregated each route to look at the distance and the average speed, and we see this

00:04:26.239 --> 00:04:31.040
interesting pattern, which I'll talk a little bit about later. But what I want to talk about first

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:36.959
is how do we get to this plot? So we're going to start with some data. So we've got about 300,000

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:44.480
rows of flight data, not a particularly large data set, but nothing either. We've got information

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:50.480
about when the flight departed, both when it's scheduled to depart and when it actually departed,

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:57.519
when it arrived, who flew it, which airline, what the flight number was, what the plane tail

00:04:57.519 --> 00:05:05.519
number was, etc. The time it spent in the air, the distance, and so on. If you look carefully,

00:05:06.079 --> 00:05:11.920
you'll notice there's no variable here for speed. We've got the time and the distance,

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:15.040
but we don't have the speed. So our first task is going to be to compute that.

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:21.600
And to do that, we're going to use a function from the dplyr package called mutate. The job

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:25.119
of mutate is to create new variables, and so we're going to say we want to create a new variable

00:05:25.119 --> 00:05:29.760
called speed, and we're going to compute that variable. That's just the speed, it's just the

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:37.359
distance in miles divided by the time in hours to give us miles per hour. Now here, airtime is a

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:42.959
minute, so we just have to do a little conversion there. So this should mostly look straightforward.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:50.399
There's a bit of weird syntax here. This thing is called the pipe, and it's the easiest to pronounce

00:05:50.399 --> 00:05:54.959
then. I'll come back to the pipe a couple of times in this talk because it's a really

00:05:54.959 --> 00:05:59.839
important and interesting idea, but for now, just in your head when you see this, read this as then.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:04.720
So we take the flight's data, then we mutate it to add a variable called speed,

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:11.519
which is this function of distance and airtime. So the next thing we want to do is we want to

00:06:11.519 --> 00:06:16.880
summarize each route, and a route is a combination of origin and destination.

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:22.399
So the first thing we know is we're going to declare that, like this is our unit of analysis.

00:06:22.399 --> 00:06:27.200
We're going to say we want to group by the origin and destination, and then we want to summarize it

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:32.399
to compute these three variables. We're going to compute the distance, the speed, and then just

00:06:32.399 --> 00:06:38.000
count the number of flights. Now you might kind of wonder when you're like thinking about this in

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:43.920
your head, you've got a flight route between two airports, shouldn't the distance always be the

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:49.760
same? Hopefully, yes. Like obviously the speed's going to change because sometimes planes take

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:54.480
longer, but hopefully that distance should always be the same. Here I'm just using mean as an easy

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:59.279
way to like get that. If you're doing a real analysis here, you might also want to compute

00:06:59.279 --> 00:07:03.920
like the standard deviation of distance, because if that's not zero, that's telling you something

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:09.679
pretty weird about what's going on with these airports. So we've got the distance, we compute

00:07:09.679 --> 00:07:15.760
the average distance, the average speed, removing any missing values, and then we also count the

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:20.320
number of observations. And this is good because you know whenever you're doing an aggregate,

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:24.640
you want to know the number of observations you're aggregating over, because you know there's hardly

00:07:24.640 --> 00:07:28.799
any observations. There's going to be a lot of variability there, and they're probably not that

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:32.959
interesting to look at. And so in fact that's the next thing I'm going to do, is I'm going to say

00:07:32.959 --> 00:07:38.480
just give me the rows, give me the route that have at least 10 flights, 10 observations.

00:07:40.799 --> 00:07:45.679
So now we've added that variable, we've grouped it, we've summarized it,

00:07:45.679 --> 00:07:50.079
filtered it, now we want to turn it into a plot. So we're going to switch from the dply package

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:57.920
to the ggplot2 package, and the key idea of ggplot2 is that a visualization is just a mapping

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:03.679
between variables in your data, the things that you can perceive, which in ggplot2 we call

00:08:03.679 --> 00:08:09.760
aesthetics, and we use AES for short. So here we're saying we want to create a plot that is going to

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:15.839
map the x position on the plots to distance, the y position to speed, and then we're going to

00:08:15.839 --> 00:08:22.720
visualize each observation with a point, giving us a scatterplot. So ggplot2, it's a little bit

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:26.799
different to other plotting systems that uses this idea called the grammar of graphics. It doesn't

00:08:26.799 --> 00:08:32.239
give you this canned set of named graphics like scatterplot, lineplot, pie chart, etc. It gives

00:08:32.239 --> 00:08:38.080
you these primitives, you map your variables to things that you can perceive, you pick the geom

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:44.000
or geometric object you want to display them with, and then ggplot2 does the rest. And so that gives

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:52.719
us this plot. You can see there's like a pretty sort of pronounced curve here. Short flights,

00:08:52.719 --> 00:08:58.799
their speed is basically dominated by takeoff and landing, which are much slower, and the longer a

00:08:58.799 --> 00:09:03.520
flight is, the more time it can spend as kind of optimal, both the more time it can spend at like

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:08.719
the optimal cruising speed, and the more likely the airline is to use a bigger, faster flight to travel.

00:09:10.239 --> 00:09:15.520
There's one group of weird points which kind of don't follow this pattern. I looked at these just

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:21.440
a little bit. These are a bit weird because these are the airports that are not in the continental

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:26.159
United States, which is a little bit surprising because that's what was supposed to be the only

00:09:26.159 --> 00:09:30.719
thing in this data set. So again, real data analysis, you want to drill into that a little

00:09:30.719 --> 00:09:35.359
bit more, but you know, very, very common part of the process. You create a plot and you see something

00:09:35.359 --> 00:09:39.840
weird and it represents some data quality problem that you're going to want to cycle back to and

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:48.960
figure out what's up. Okay, so that, just very, very quickly, here's a little bit of R code that does

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:56.400
something, you know, small but realistic in a data analysis. What makes this tick? So the first thing

00:09:56.400 --> 00:10:01.280
I want to talk about, or to dive into a little bit detail, is just that that mutate function.

00:10:01.919 --> 00:10:07.919
And to do that, I'm going to create a data frame that just contains those two variables we care

00:10:07.919 --> 00:10:14.239
about, distance and airtime, and just the first six observations. Now, if you've never seen R code

00:10:14.239 --> 00:10:21.520
before, two kind of tricks. First, this arrow thing, this less than dash is R's primary assignment

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:29.359
operator, that's what you use to create variables. And then, oops, I messed up my transition there,

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:38.239
this dot does not represent calling a method, it's just a regular symbol and a function. So

00:10:38.239 --> 00:10:42.880
if you're coming from Python or many other languages like Java, it's going to take you a

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:47.679
while to get your head around this. You're not calling the frame a method of the data object,

00:10:47.679 --> 00:10:53.039
you're calling this data dot frame function. And that's the function in R we use to create

00:10:53.039 --> 00:10:59.599
data frames, which is the data structure used to store rectangular data. And then, just going to

00:10:59.599 --> 00:11:04.479
recapitulate the code we saw before, I'm going to take that data frame, then I'm going to mutate it,

00:11:04.479 --> 00:11:11.679
computing the speed. And the pipe here is just syntactic sugar. All the pipe does, it takes the

00:11:11.679 --> 00:11:17.919
thing on the left-hand side and puts it into the first argument of the function on the right-hand

00:11:17.919 --> 00:11:28.640
side of the pipe. So it's just syntactic sugar for this. So here it is with the pipe. If I rewrite it

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:37.200
without the pipe, we now see that df is just the first argument to mutate. The pipes is this really

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:42.159
nice feature because so often when you're working on a data analysis, you do these multiple

00:11:42.159 --> 00:11:47.359
transformations. The pipe just allows us to write that linearly. Coming back to that

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:50.080
another once more before we're done here.

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:58.080
The next thing that's kind of interesting about this code is inside this function,

00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:03.679
we refer to distance and airtime just like the regular variables that you've just defined with

00:12:03.679 --> 00:12:08.239
assignment. But they're not regular variables. They're variables that exist inside this data

00:12:08.239 --> 00:12:15.679
frame. And you'll see this pattern a lot in R that many, many functions allow you to write code

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:22.000
that works kind of inside a data frame as if you'd assigned the individual columns,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.679
the individual variables of a data frame, the top-level variables in your program.

00:12:27.039 --> 00:12:33.200
And kind of even crazier, you can actually mix both variables inside the data frame and

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:39.280
variables outside the data frame. Now, this absolutely can lead to really confusing and

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:46.479
hard to read code. But most of the time, it allows you to really elegantly describe what you're doing

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:50.320
to the variables in your data set without having to have a bunch of additional syntax to say,

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:53.919
oh, this variable's inside that data frame, this variable's inside that data frame.

00:12:53.919 --> 00:12:57.520
Or most of the time, it's like these variables are all inside the data frame, and I've got to

00:12:57.520 --> 00:13:02.080
repeat the name of the data frame many, many times or use some other kind of sentinel to say, hey,

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:08.559
this is something going on inside this data frame. So why does this work? And this is kind

00:13:08.559 --> 00:13:15.599
of the first surprising feature of R. And that is it has first-class abstract syntax trees

00:13:15.599 --> 00:13:21.679
and first-class environments. So what does that mean? So every programming language

00:13:21.679 --> 00:13:27.359
has abstract syntax trees and has environments. Every programming language has some way

00:13:27.359 --> 00:13:32.400
to represent the structure of code, typically in some kind of tree form after you've fully

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:38.080
passed it out and dealt with all the operator precedence issues, and some way to associate names

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:44.400
with values, which is what in R we call environments. Now, some languages, a few

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:49.359
languages have first-class abstract syntax trees. This is kind of the famous thing about lists,

00:13:49.359 --> 00:13:55.520
right, that you can actually program on code. You can program code because there's a representation,

00:13:55.599 --> 00:14:02.000
a programmable representation of code. So R has that, and additionally, it has first-class

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:08.159
environments. You can actually look at the way that names are bound to values, introspect on that,

00:14:08.159 --> 00:14:15.200
and modify that. And as far as I know, that is unique in the spectrum of all programming languages.

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:20.640
Almost certainly some programming language that I don't know about that does it, but none of the

00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:24.479
mainstream programming environments, or even the sort of weirder ones in the pocket of the day,

00:14:24.479 --> 00:14:31.039
have this feature. And this definitely makes R code harder to optimize,

00:14:31.039 --> 00:14:37.359
but it also gives R this unparalleled ability to create domain-specific languages for solving

00:14:37.359 --> 00:14:43.840
problems, and we can apply that so well to data science. That's what gives us the tools like

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:51.359
dplyr and ggplot2 that allow us to kind of turn our data science thoughts, our data science words,

00:14:51.359 --> 00:14:58.159
into code in a way that's generally pretty natural. And it's also what gives us the ability

00:14:58.159 --> 00:15:06.080
to create tools like dbplyr. So dbplyr is a dplyr backend. A backend for dplyr is just,

00:15:06.080 --> 00:15:12.239
you have the same syntax, but it's the computation in some other way. So when you're using dplyr,

00:15:12.239 --> 00:15:17.760
you're going to connect to a database as the db might suggest to you, and you're going to write

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:24.880
dplyr code just like you normally do, and dbplyr is going to convert that to SQL. So in this case,

00:15:24.880 --> 00:15:31.280
it's going to generate this SQL with a CTE that does, that computes the speed variable,

00:15:31.280 --> 00:15:38.239
and then a group summary. This isn't exactly, you know, the SQL you might write by hand in particular.

00:15:38.239 --> 00:15:42.880
We've kind of very conservatively quoted every single possible variable name just to make sure

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:46.799
it's not a special name inside the data frame, and you might do a few things different. You might

00:15:46.799 --> 00:15:52.400
give those various informative names, but overall, like dbplyr does a pretty good job.

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:58.159
And it does this in a pretty, like the implementation of dbplyr is still pretty

00:15:58.159 --> 00:16:04.400
crazy to me because it does this by defining a special environment where like mean instead of

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:11.280
like calculating the mean actually generates some SQL text that then gets inlined into this query.

00:16:12.159 --> 00:16:17.760
It's pretty, this is one of the, my kind of personal favorite packages that I've worked with.

00:16:19.119 --> 00:16:23.599
But lots, there are lots of other uses of this in R as well. Just two I wanted to highlight are

00:16:23.599 --> 00:16:31.200
the ompr package for mixed integer programming. Here you can define relationships between integer

00:16:31.200 --> 00:16:37.520
variables, define like objectives and constraints, and then allow ompr to go away and like solve that

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:46.159
problem for you. Another package, Greta, designed for Bayesian statistics. It uses a syntax like

00:16:46.159 --> 00:16:50.880
really inspired by what you might've seen in a Bayesian statistics class. So here I'm just

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:55.599
defining a very simple linear model, Bayesian linear model, where I'm defining a prior

00:16:55.599 --> 00:17:02.400
distribution for my intercept and slope, describing how the mean is a function of the intercept and

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:10.719
the slope and the data, how I expect the distribution of the predictor to be a normal

00:17:10.719 --> 00:17:14.479
distribution with that mean I just computed and that standard deviation defined earlier,

00:17:14.479 --> 00:17:23.520
and I can go away with it. And this ability to kind of tailor the way that R code looks to match

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:29.280
other environments, other ways of, other notational systems, I think is really,

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:37.119
really powerful and really, really cool. And again, R can do that because it has these first

00:17:37.119 --> 00:17:42.640
class abstract syntax trees, first class environments, gives you this incredible ability

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:48.640
to create domain specific languages that solves some small part of the data science process.

00:17:54.719 --> 00:17:56.880
Next, I wanted to talk a little bit more about the pipe.

00:17:57.839 --> 00:18:03.199
Because if you look at this pipeline that I show you earlier and kind of squint your eyes a little

00:18:03.199 --> 00:18:09.359
bit, you might say, oh, well, couldn't we just write that using like method chaining with Python?

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:17.599
Like very, very similar, right? Just basically changing that pipe for a dot at each point.

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:21.920
But there's something that's profoundly different about that pipe.

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:30.160
And that is at each point, each element of that pipeline can come from a different package.

00:18:32.800 --> 00:18:40.000
And the thing that makes this work is kind of surprising and mind blowing. And when I first

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:45.599
encountered R, it took me several years to really understand. And that is that in R,

00:18:45.599 --> 00:18:55.119
methods belong to functions, not classes. So I don't want to go into all the details of this,

00:18:55.119 --> 00:18:59.439
but if you kind of think about object-oriented systems, every object-oriented system has these

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:05.199
functions that you call and classes that you use and the methods are sort of the intersection.

00:19:06.079 --> 00:19:11.920
You can think of it as sort of a 2D table. That you've got functions and you've got classes.

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:20.000
And most programming languages kind of organize their OOP system like row-wise and R kind of

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:27.359
organizes it column-wise. Obviously, that's like a great caricature of what's going on,

00:19:27.359 --> 00:19:32.319
but I think that that's kind of like an orthogonal way of thinking about object-oriented programming.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:40.560
And for a long time, this was pretty quirky. Like two languages used this, Common Lisp and R.

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:45.520
But recently, another programming language has come along that also uses this style

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:52.400
of programming language, and that's Julia. And I think it's one of the things that Julia folks

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:59.040
really attribute to the ease of reusing code in Julia is this style of object-oriented programming.

00:19:59.040 --> 00:20:04.800
It just seems to fit particularly with kind of like scientific computing and data science so well.

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:13.760
So, the consequences of this are pretty profound. This ability component of that pipeline can come

00:20:13.760 --> 00:20:20.160
from a different package. It means that we don't need these really big kind of monolithic packages

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:24.719
like Pandas, like Scikit-learn. That when you're assembling a pipeline, you can assemble pieces

00:20:24.719 --> 00:20:29.839
from all over the place, which means the life of software developers is much easier because

00:20:29.839 --> 00:20:34.079
they can develop these small reusable pieces in isolation without having to consider

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:42.160
this giant other package. Okay, so we've talked about two weird things, about two surprising

00:20:42.160 --> 00:20:46.560
things about R. The first one, first-class abstract and vector use in environments,

00:20:46.560 --> 00:20:52.560
which allows you to create these domain-specific languages. For data science, we have the fact

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:59.439
that methods belong to functions, not classes, which allows us to write pipelines that combine

00:20:59.439 --> 00:21:05.119
tools from many, many different places. And the last thing I want to talk about is kind of

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:10.880
hard to describe, kind of crazy at first sight, and that's like when you install a package in R,

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:18.719
generally like 99% of the time, you just install it into some like a global repository of packages

00:21:18.719 --> 00:21:24.719
on your computer. Because when you're working with R, most projects don't need a virtual

00:21:24.719 --> 00:21:32.079
environment, and most people using R can just share the same set of packages across all of

00:21:32.079 --> 00:21:37.760
their projects, and things by and large just work. Now, obviously, if you really care about long-term

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:41.520
reproducibility, you're going to have to do more than that. You are going to have to capture your

00:21:41.520 --> 00:21:47.920
exact version of your dependencies using some, you know, virtual env-like tool in R. One is called

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:52.319
renv, developed by one of my colleagues, but there's plenty of other options as well.

00:21:53.199 --> 00:21:59.680
And the reason this is the case is that package development in R is really highly centralized.

00:22:00.959 --> 00:22:07.040
And I think it's easy to think of centralization generally as kind of a bad thing, or at least

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:13.680
that's kind of the way that the tech is currently trending, is we want to distribute things as much

00:22:13.680 --> 00:22:19.359
as possible. But there are some big advantages to centralization. And so I just want to kind of

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:29.760
briefly compare like CRAN, the Comprehensive R Archive Network, which probably supplies like 99%

00:22:29.760 --> 00:22:36.319
of R packages installed in the wild, versus PyPI, which maybe does 80% of package,

00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:42.640
private packages installed in the wild. And the thing that's like fundamentally different about

00:22:42.640 --> 00:22:49.839
CRAN compared to PyPI, and pretty much every other modern kind of software distribution tool,

00:22:49.839 --> 00:22:57.680
is that it enforces package compatibility. So at any moment in time, every package in CRAN

00:22:57.680 --> 00:23:02.959
must work with all of the current version of all of its dependencies on CRAN.

00:23:04.959 --> 00:23:11.439
And no lie, this is a huge amount of work. This makes life much, much harder for developers.

00:23:11.439 --> 00:23:16.479
If you're developing a Python package, you can easily set up a GitHub action that automatically

00:23:16.479 --> 00:23:25.199
deploys the PyPI whenever you do a release. Whenever you tag, you can completely 100%

00:23:25.199 --> 00:23:32.800
automate that process, and it just works. In R, the process is much harder. You've got to go

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:40.079
through the system that's like, I don't know, 80% automated and 20% human audited. And if you

00:23:40.560 --> 00:23:46.000
make a breaking change to your package, it's your responsibility to communicate that

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:53.680
to all of the people who use your package on CRAN. And that's a lot of work. But it comes with

00:23:53.680 --> 00:24:01.199
like this big payoff for users that, by and large, they can just grab a bunch of packages from CRAN,

00:24:01.199 --> 00:24:07.680
and they all work. And I think this is maybe one of the reasons that CRAN is so much more than

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:15.119
PyPI. Obviously, there are other reasons like the Python. Generally, the number of Python

00:24:15.119 --> 00:24:20.880
programmers is much, much bigger than the number of R programmers. But I think this is not easy

00:24:21.439 --> 00:24:28.479
to publish. It's not as easy to publish a package with R. And that leads to fewer packages,

00:24:28.479 --> 00:24:34.079
but they tend to be easier for people to work with. The other kind of last interesting fact

00:24:34.640 --> 00:24:40.479
is that the definition of a package in R is really baked into the language itself. It's

00:24:40.479 --> 00:24:44.719
included in the standard library. It includes this tool called R command check, which runs a

00:24:44.719 --> 00:24:50.479
bunch of standardized checks and inspects the documentation and tests and stuff in various ways.

00:24:50.479 --> 00:25:00.719
And it's been there for day one, basically, of R. Day 300 or something. But very, very early on,

00:25:00.880 --> 00:25:07.520
really key part of the success of R has been the ability to distribute binaries that are built on

00:25:07.520 --> 00:25:12.719
the centralized CRAN repository. And people have been able to install these on Windows for years

00:25:12.719 --> 00:25:18.719
and years and years. I think that's one reason that the distribution of operating systems is

00:25:18.719 --> 00:25:24.000
quite different between R and Python. Because I think something like 80% of R users are on Windows.

00:25:24.719 --> 00:25:29.280
The other 20% roughly split between Mac and Linux. And I looked this up, but I've already

00:25:29.280 --> 00:25:33.760
forgotten what it was for Python. But I think it's much, much lower. Maybe like 40% of Python

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:37.680
users are on Windows. So I think just one of these kind of other differences in the language.

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:49.760
So those are three things. R has top level, first class, abstract industries and environments.

00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:58.160
R methods belong to functions, not classes. And most users don't need a virtual environment,

00:25:58.160 --> 00:26:02.079
or many users don't need a virtual environment, because package development is highly simple.

00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:08.959
I think hopefully these are three things that as a Python user or as users of some other language,

00:26:08.959 --> 00:26:19.040
you're like, wow, that's odd. But hopefully I've also shown you that these have some pretty cool

00:26:19.040 --> 00:26:25.040
consequences as well. And so when you see them, I hope you think not just like, oh, this is weird

00:26:25.040 --> 00:26:32.880
and wrong, but like, oh, this is different and interesting. Now I do like, I don't know,

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:39.760
I spend like 90% of my life in R. I do like everything in R. I just did a secret Santa

00:26:39.760 --> 00:26:44.239
for my family where I programmed the whole thing in R and sent out the email automatically. But

00:26:44.239 --> 00:26:50.880
there's lots of other people who work for the same company that I do. And the goal of our company is

00:26:50.880 --> 00:26:56.319
not just to make cool R packages, but to really have a positive impact generally on data science

00:26:56.959 --> 00:27:02.640
and technical communication. So I want to talk a little bit just briefly. I don't think people

00:27:02.640 --> 00:27:06.079
talking about the companies is that interesting in general. So I want to go through this pretty

