together, particularly utilizing shared high-power computational infrastructure. Package Manager

00:30:36.800 --> 00:30:41.199
helps make sure all of your dependencies are in line with your corporate policy, and everyone's

00:30:41.199 --> 00:30:47.119
using the same version in the same place. And then, surprise, PositCloud helps you do those same

00:30:47.119 --> 00:30:57.920
things but in the cloud. So to finish up, I want to talk about a few of the open source tools that

00:30:57.920 --> 00:31:06.160
we're currently working on that are specifically designed to support multiple languages. And the

00:31:06.160 --> 00:31:12.719
first one I want to talk about is Quarto, which is a tool designed to help you publish stuff, to make

00:31:12.719 --> 00:31:19.920
documents. The key idea of Quarto is you're going to start with some document. Those two types of

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:24.560
documents you might start with. You might start with something like a Jupyter Notebook, where you

00:31:24.560 --> 00:31:30.640
have text, where you have code, and you have the results of that code. Or you might start with

00:31:30.640 --> 00:31:36.000
something like an R Markdown, more like an R Markdown document, now a Quarto Markdown document that just

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:42.959
has the text and the code, and you need to run that code. And that code can be in Python or R

00:31:42.959 --> 00:31:48.959
or Julia or, you know, pretty much anything. In both cases, we're going to end up with a Markdown document.

00:31:48.959 --> 00:31:55.920
Markdown is a really great, we think, like, format because it's a text format. It's easily

00:31:55.920 --> 00:32:01.040
diffable. You can check it as a commit, you can share it with people, easy to write by hand,

00:32:01.359 --> 00:32:07.439
by hand if you need to. But even more importantly than that, Markdown gets you into the Pandoc

00:32:07.439 --> 00:32:13.839
ecosystem. And if you haven't heard of Pandoc before, it's this really amazing tool for doing

00:32:13.839 --> 00:32:19.839
document transformations, basically. And by building on top of Pandoc, that allows Quarto

00:32:19.839 --> 00:32:26.160
to produce things like Word documents and PowerPoint presentations and PDFs and HTML files.

00:32:26.160 --> 00:32:31.680
You can even publish, kind of fully roundtrip, to publish a notebook from the end of it, if your

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:36.400
input is something else, or even in some cases it's useful to kind of roundtrip, because some

00:32:36.400 --> 00:32:46.800
of the tools I'll talk about shortly. So Quarto, like, helps you turn your words and your code

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:51.839
into some document that you can share with others. It also provides tools for when you've got, like,

00:32:51.839 --> 00:32:56.479
a bunch of documents and you want to convey some bigger story, whether that's through a website or

00:32:56.479 --> 00:33:05.439
a blog or a book. Now, if you're an R user, this might look kind of familiar. And that's no surprise,

00:33:05.439 --> 00:33:10.880
because Quarto was very much inspired by our 10 years of experience with R Master,

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:18.880
which really, I think, convinced us that this core idea of literate programming for data science is

00:33:18.880 --> 00:33:25.040
the right approach. That you want to be able to create reproducible documents that, when you,

00:33:25.040 --> 00:33:30.880
when the data changes, you can rerun your code, combine it with your pros, and get a new Word

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:38.079
document or HTML page or PowerPoint slide. But in the time that since R Markdown was created,

00:33:38.079 --> 00:33:42.560
like, the number of languages used for data science has increased. It continues to increase.

00:33:43.119 --> 00:33:48.959
And so the, and so while, like, R Markdown did support other languages, you could absolutely

00:33:48.959 --> 00:33:55.280
use Python inside of R Markdown today, you still have to have R installed. And that's not, like,

00:33:55.280 --> 00:33:59.520
super compelling, right? If you're a Python user and you want to create a nice document,

00:33:59.520 --> 00:34:04.319
you don't want to install R. So the goal of Quarto is it's ground up reimagining. We're

00:34:04.319 --> 00:34:10.959
going to make it fully multi-language, fully multi-engine. So regardless of what language

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:16.080
you're doing your data science in, whether it's R or Python or Jupyter or something that doesn't

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:20.479
even exist today, Quarto is going to support that. Quarto is going to be the engine that helps you

00:34:20.479 --> 00:34:25.439
combine your pros and your code and your results to create some beautiful documents to share with

00:34:25.439 --> 00:34:37.679
others. And generally, one of the goals of Quarto is to help make it easier to write scientifically,

00:34:37.679 --> 00:34:42.719
to do scientific writing inside of Markdown. And some of you might have seen this kind of

00:34:42.719 --> 00:34:49.520
humorous depiction of the tools you might currently use to write scientific documents.

00:34:49.520 --> 00:34:54.800
So, you know, you can start with, you might use Word, which starts really simple, but

00:34:54.800 --> 00:35:02.560
rapidly gets very, very complex. As soon as you add in citations or complex figures,

00:35:02.560 --> 00:35:07.679
it gets really, really complicated, really, really quickly. You could, of course, use LaTeX,

00:35:07.679 --> 00:35:15.120
which starts hard and stays hard. Once you've got the ability to do a LaTeX document,

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:22.560
you've mastered the art of Googling for LaTeX syntax, it doesn't get that much harder,

00:35:22.560 --> 00:35:29.120
but very, very hard and not accessible to most people. So Markdown is a great way to start,

00:35:29.120 --> 00:35:34.479
but if you're using Markdown for scientific writing, you kind of rapidly hit some limitations,

00:35:34.479 --> 00:35:38.320
like you're going to have to bring your own tooling for combining multiple files, you're

00:35:38.320 --> 00:35:42.080
going to have to figure out the new syntax for the various types of things you want to do in

00:35:42.080 --> 00:35:48.800
scientific writing. And so the idea of Quarto, the aspiration for Quarto is to really start

00:35:49.360 --> 00:35:57.600
as easy as Word and only get a little bit harder over time. And Quarto does that by building a

00:35:57.600 --> 00:36:04.719
bunch of extensions on top of Pandoc, extensions for things like citations. So you can just copy

00:36:04.719 --> 00:36:11.040
and paste a DOI in and you automatically get a nicely formatted citation. Rich cross-references

00:36:11.040 --> 00:36:17.760
between longer documents, equations using LaTeX math, complex diagrams and multi-fixed panels,

00:36:17.760 --> 00:36:22.000
all of these things that you need when writing, creating scientific documents.

00:36:22.959 --> 00:36:27.760
And the thing that's great about all of these things is they're built on top of this extension

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:34.159
mechanism provided by Pandoc. And the neat thing about this is that this extension mechanism is

00:36:34.159 --> 00:36:39.840
written on top of the abstract syntax tree of the Markdown documents, written on top of the

00:36:39.840 --> 00:36:45.520
semantics of the document, not on the text format. So if you've ever tried to do some of these things,

00:36:45.520 --> 00:36:51.280
introduce new syntax by hand with regular expressions, it starts off like it's doable

00:36:51.360 --> 00:36:55.919
if you want to add one extension, maybe. If you want to add two, you start to hit all of these

00:36:55.919 --> 00:37:01.919
weird edge cases and it's very, very hard to get fully correct. So Pandoc provides this really

00:37:01.919 --> 00:37:06.800
cool extension mechanism. The downside of that extension mechanism is you're going to have to

00:37:06.800 --> 00:37:12.639
learn a little bit about Lua. It's a relatively rare programming language, but it's designed to

00:37:12.639 --> 00:37:18.080
be used in exactly this situation, embedded inside other tools. So if you've used any other programming

00:37:18.080 --> 00:37:21.600
language before, whether it's R or Python or something else, you're going to be able to pick

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:29.919
up Lua very, very quickly. And then on top of those Pandoc extensions, Cordo provides an extension

00:37:29.919 --> 00:37:34.959
mechanism that makes it really easy to document your extension, to publish your extension, to share

00:37:34.959 --> 00:37:39.760
your extension with other people. So once you've figured out how to do this, the whole community

00:37:39.760 --> 00:37:48.719
can build on top of it. So here are some examples of Cordo used today. Personally, I use it for

00:37:48.719 --> 00:37:53.520
pretty much everything I write, all the books I write are in Cordo. But in the Python ecosystem,

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:58.479
you might be interested in these two projects that use it. Wes McKinney's Python for Data Analysis

00:37:58.479 --> 00:38:04.719
uses it, and the Practical Deep Learning course from Fast.ai uses it as well. And if you want to

00:38:04.719 --> 00:38:08.239
see more examples, there are many, many more, of course, on the Cordo website.

00:38:10.399 --> 00:38:16.000
So that's going to pique your interest a little bit in Cordo. I highly recommend a talk by my

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:21.199
colleague, Tom Mock, Reproducible Publications with Python Cordo, which is going to be in two

00:38:21.199 --> 00:38:31.520
days' time, two hours ago. Okay. So that's Cordo, which is primarily about publishing

00:38:31.520 --> 00:38:37.360
documents. And I kind of talked about mostly static documents, but it also allows you,

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:46.320
it also has support for particularly observable JavaScript, so you can do within-page interactivity.

00:38:47.919 --> 00:38:52.399
But there are some tasks that you need kind of like full interactivity. You want to be able to

00:38:52.399 --> 00:38:57.679
drag a slider that sends issues, a query for a database, or retrieves some data that fits a model

00:38:57.679 --> 00:39:05.120
and shows the result back. And for that sort of need, we have Shiny. So Shiny was originally

00:39:05.120 --> 00:39:10.479
an R package, and now it has a Python version as well. And it's really designed to create

00:39:10.479 --> 00:39:16.639
interactive apps and dashboards, so that you can help decision makers inside your organization,

00:39:16.639 --> 00:39:23.600
like, see what's going on with the data set. So I'm going to start with a very simple example

00:39:24.560 --> 00:39:33.280
from Shiny Live. So Shiny Live, I'll just make that a little bigger for you, Shiny Live is powered

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:39.919
by the kind of magic of Pyodide and Wasm. So here I'm running like Python and PyShiny fully in the

00:39:39.919 --> 00:39:46.879
browser. So here I've got a little PyShiny app. And you can see, as I change the slider, that the

00:39:47.199 --> 00:39:54.159
histogram changes. So how does PyShiny work? Well, there's two main components. First of all,

00:39:54.159 --> 00:40:00.399
we're going to define the UI. So here we've got a page that contains a sidebar. That's this guy,

00:40:00.399 --> 00:40:08.399
which contains a slider, and a main panel that contains a plot. So Shiny kind of separates out

00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:14.879
the view of the page from the interactivity. And the interactivity is provided by the server

00:40:14.879 --> 00:40:21.760
function, which uses some decorators to annotate this function. So this function is called

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:29.120
histogram, which lines up with the, by convention, lines up with the name of this plot in the UI.

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:35.840
So when this function runs, it's going to automatically draw this histogram, and that

00:40:35.840 --> 00:40:41.840
histogram is going to appear in that main panel. And the thing that's neat about Shiny is that you

00:40:41.840 --> 00:40:47.840
don't have to be, you have to explicitly declare the dependency. Like Shiny is going to see that

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:54.159
this plot is using the number, this interactive slider for the number of bins. And so whenever

00:40:54.159 --> 00:41:01.520
this changes, Shiny is going to automatically update that plot. So this is a very, very simple

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:09.280
example. Shiny can also do very complex things. I'm just going to show you this kind of cool

00:41:10.239 --> 00:41:17.919
example that my colleague Joe Ching put together for PyData NYC. So here we have a 3D chart.

00:41:19.679 --> 00:41:23.360
And the kind of cool thing about this, the scrutinously cool thing about this,

00:41:23.360 --> 00:41:31.840
is I can control that by moving my hand around in the webcam. Reads my hand position,

00:41:31.840 --> 00:41:37.439
feeds that into the Shiny plot, Shiny and rotates the plot. So I don't really, I don't want to go

00:41:37.679 --> 00:41:44.879
into the details of that at all, but just to show you that the power of Shiny is,

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:54.320
it goes a very, very long way. So Shiny has this kind of dual design for both data scientists and

00:41:54.320 --> 00:41:59.679
software engineers. If you're a data scientist, you can start creating web apps, interactive web

00:41:59.679 --> 00:42:06.399
apps with like very little HTML, CSS or JavaScript skills. It uses this reactive programming model,

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:13.439
which makes it interactively easy to get start with. And it builds on our many years of Shiny

00:42:13.439 --> 00:42:19.280
for R and seeing what data scientists actually want to do. But it's also designed for software

00:42:19.280 --> 00:42:26.879
engineers. So if you know HTML and CSS and JavaScript, you can use that. And you get to

00:42:26.879 --> 00:42:33.040
like learn about this really kind of amazing programming paradigm called reactive programming.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:39.919
And just sort of very, very conceptually reactive programming is really all about creating a DAG,

00:42:39.919 --> 00:42:45.280
a directed acyclic graph from your inputs to your outputs. And that what Shiny does is when one of

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:51.679
your inputs changes, it knows how to automatically invalidate all of the things downstream and

00:42:51.679 --> 00:42:59.679
recompute them as needed. And this reactive model is relatively simple, but surprisingly rich. It

00:42:59.679 --> 00:43:03.840
gives you all of this kind of, once you master the idea, it gives you all this stuff kind of for

00:43:03.840 --> 00:43:12.479
free. The last thing I want to talk about today is Bedeva, which is a set of tools for R and Python

00:43:12.479 --> 00:43:19.040
for MLOps. So that of course begs the question, what is MLOps? And there are a lot of competing

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:25.600
and conflicting definitions in play today, but kind of our framing of MLOps is a set of practices

00:43:25.600 --> 00:43:31.520
to deploy and maintain ML models in production, both reliably and efficiently.

00:43:32.320 --> 00:43:36.800
And here we're thinking mostly about kind of human efficiency. How do we make this as easy

00:43:36.800 --> 00:43:44.080
as possible for the data scientists? So Bedeva stays out of the initial model building process

00:43:44.080 --> 00:43:48.479
where you collect data and understand and clean it and visualize it and try a bunch of models,

00:43:48.479 --> 00:43:56.320
evaluate them. You bring your own, whether that's XGBoost in R or Scikit-learn in Python,

00:43:56.320 --> 00:44:02.000
Bedeva is going to support you no matter what you do. Bedeva starts to play when you want to get

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:06.239
that model into production. And if you're going to put a model in production, we really believe

00:44:06.239 --> 00:44:10.320
the first thing you need to do is version that model. And that's really important because it

00:44:10.320 --> 00:44:15.360
allows you to track how it changes over time. And if you accidentally screw up, you can easily

00:44:15.360 --> 00:44:23.280
revert the previous version. Then Bedeva is going to help you deploy the model. In the most general

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:29.520
case, this is basically developing a Docker, creating a Docker container that runs a server

00:44:29.520 --> 00:44:35.679
that exposes a JSON API that other services can hit with data and get predictions back out.

00:44:36.959 --> 00:44:41.919
If you're using PositConnect, our tool that helps data scientists communicate with others

00:44:41.919 --> 00:44:47.280
in the organization, this all gets handled behind the hood and you can deploy your model with one

00:44:47.280 --> 00:44:53.600
line of code. Importantly, this doesn't just deploy the model, it also deploys some documentation.

00:44:54.719 --> 00:44:59.360
Currently, the documentation for the API, like how you actually use it. But in the future,

00:44:59.360 --> 00:45:04.560
this also is going to support publishing documentation about the model itself through

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:09.840
the popular model card framework. And then finally, you're going to want to monitor that model.

00:45:09.840 --> 00:45:14.239
And because you've got all these versions of the previous model, very easy to track what's

00:45:14.239 --> 00:45:20.879
going on, what's happening to your model. If that sounds interesting, I highly recommend

00:45:20.879 --> 00:45:24.479
attending the talk by my colleague, Isabel Zimmerman,

00:45:24.479 --> 00:45:29.199
Practical ML Ops with Bedeva Models, which is happening in one day, two and a half hours ago.

