00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:37.840
really easy to use, like, really easy to get up and running with. With Shiny, like, to use Shiny

00:49:37.840 --> 00:49:43.840
effectively, you have to learn a little bit about this reactive programming model. And it's basically

00:49:43.840 --> 00:49:50.959
our belief that if you put in some legitimately hard work doing that, that's really going to pay

00:49:50.959 --> 00:49:56.800
off when you start to create much, much, much more complex apps, where there are many changing

00:49:56.800 --> 00:50:05.040
inputs and many intermediate calculations and many results. The way that reactivity works allows you

00:50:05.040 --> 00:50:11.760
to kind of create these things that just don't turn up and turn into this nightmare spaghetti

00:50:11.760 --> 00:50:17.120
of, like, events changing things. And then you can change one thing and sometimes things change

00:50:17.120 --> 00:50:21.120
that you don't want to change. And other times things don't change when they should. Reactivity

00:50:21.120 --> 00:50:26.800
is just such a great model for solving that problem that we believe that a little bit of investment

00:50:26.800 --> 00:50:35.520
there kind of pays off in the long run. Yeah, no, that makes total sense. Awesome. There's so

